Heart Disease Prediction¶

Tracy Guo¶

Sep 8th, 2019

In this project, I created visualizations of factors that increase risk of heart disease with Python matplotlib and seaborn. I then constructed logistic regression, random forest, k-nearest neighbor, and support vector machine algorithms to predict heart disease in patients with Python pandas, numpy and scikit-learn. In the last section, I evaluated and compared performances of models with confusion matrices and ROC curves. My personal goal for this proejct is to practice machine learning techniques and enrich my data visualization skills.

The dataset comes from the UCI Heart dataset on Kaggle.

You could access it through this link: https://www.kaggle.com/sonumj/heart-disease-dataset-from-uci

Distribution of heart disease in the dataset¶

As the chart below presents, the number of patients with and without heart disease are relatively similar.

In [140]:
sns.set(style="whitegrid")
sns.countplot(x=heart.target, data=heart,  palette= ("cadetblue","lightcoral"))
plt.title("Distribution of heart disease in dataset" )
plt.xlabel("Disease Status")
plt.xticks([0,1], labels=("No Heart Disease", "Heart Disease"))
plt.ylabel("Count")
plt.show()

Age Distribution of Patients¶

While many may assume that heart diseases are more frequent among older people, this dataset tells a different story. Age of patients without heart dieases has a higher mean and lower standard diviationthan that of patients with heart disease.

In [141]:
sns.set(style="whitegrid")
sns.kdeplot(heart["age"][heart["target"]==0], shade=True, color="cadetblue")
sns.kdeplot(heart["age"][heart["target"]==1], shade=True, color="lightcoral") 
plt.title('Age Distribution of Patients')
plt.legend(("No Heart Disease", "Heart Disease"))
plt.xlabel("Age")
plt.ylabel("Frequency")
plt.show()

Maximum Heart Rate Achieved Across Age, by Disease Status¶

Given the interesting discovery on age in the previous chart, I then explored how other variables differ by disease status across age. As the following chart shows, patients with heart diseases have overall higher maxium heart rate achieved than that of patients without heart diseases. Perhaps this variables is an important indicator for having heart disease.

In [193]:
sns.set(style="whitegrid")

sns.scatterplot(x="age", y="thalach", data=heart[heart["target"]==1],color="lightcoral")
plt.title("Maximum Heart Rate Achieved Across Age,by Disease Status")
plt.legend(loc="lower left",labels=("No Heart Disease", "Heart Disease"))
plt.xlabel("Age")
plt.ylabel("Maximum Heart Rate Achieved ")
plt.show()

Further, the majority of patients with heart diseases also did not have excercise induced angina. This could be another factor associated to heart disease risk.

Correlation Heatmap of all variables in the dataset¶

Since all variables in this dataset measures health of the cardiovascular system, I also plotted a correlation heatmap to ensure no variables are highly correlated with each other. As the following figure reveals, correlations between all variables are ralatively low.

In [195]:
#Create a mask to hide the repeated parts of the map
mask = np.zeros_like(heart.corr(), dtype=np.bool)
mask[np.triu_indices_from(mask)] = True
sns.heatmap(heart.corr(),xticklabels=heart.columns, yticklabels=heart.columns, mask=mask, cmap="GnBu")
plt.title("Correlation Heatmap")
plt.show()

Section 2: Machine Learning Models¶

2.1 Logistic Regression Model¶

In [128]:
#Define x and y 
X=heart[heart.columns[0:13]]
y=heart["target"]
In [198]:
#Normalize data
X_norm = (X - np.min(X)) / (np.max(X) - np.min(X)).values
In [211]:
#Split data into training and test sets: 80% will be training data and 20% will be test data
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test=train_test_split(X_norm,y, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)
In [340]:
#Fit the logistic regression model 
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
lg_model=LogisticRegression(random_state = 10).fit(X_train, y_train)

accuracy_scores.append(accuracy)
In [342]:
#Construct the confusion matrix 
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
y_predicted=lg_model.predict(X_test)
log_con= pd.DataFrame(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_predicted))
log_con.columns=["Predicted: No Disease", "Predicted: Disease"]
log_con.rename(index={0: "Actual: No Disease", 1: "Actual: Disease"},inplace=True)
sns.heatmap(log_con, annot=True, cmap="GnBu")
plt.title("Confusion Matrix for Logistic Regression Model")
plt.show()
In [422]:
#Present in-depth report of the logistic regression model
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report
#Present more detailed report
#Precision is the positive perdictive value of the model 
#Recall is the sensitivity of the test
print(classification_report(y_test, y_predicted))

In [343]:
#Construct the ROC curve for the Logistic Regression Model
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt 

auc=roc_auc_score(y_test, y_predicted)
y_prob=lg_model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]

fpr, tpr, ther=roc_curve(y_test, y_prob)
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label="Logistic Regression(auc=%0.2f)"%auc)
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], "o--")
plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title("ROC Curve of Logistic Regression Model")
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.show()

To summarize, the accuracy of the logistic regression model is 85.25 percent. Around 85% of patients that the model predicted to have heart disease actually had heart disease; 85% of paitents who actually had heart disease received correct prediction from the model.

2.3 K Nearest Neighbor¶

In [316]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier

#find the best k value by plotting out the accuracy scores
train_scores=[]
test_scores=[]
for k in range (1,40,2):
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    knn.fit(X_train, y_train)
    train_score=knn.score(X_train, y_train)
    test_score=knn.score(X_test, y_test)
    train_scores.append(train_score)
    test_scores.append(test_score)

plt.plot(range(1, 40, 2), train_scores, marker='o')
plt.plot(range(1, 40, 2), test_scores, marker="x")
plt.xlabel("k neighbors")
plt.ylabel("Testing accuracy Score")
plt.show()
In [363]:
#From the chart above, k=7 seems to yield the best result
knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=7)
knn_model= knn.fit(X_train, y_train)
knn_accuracy= knn.score(X_test, y_test)*100
#print("The accuracy of the KNN model is: %.2f percent" %knn_accuracy)
accuracy_scores.append(knn_accuracy)

To conclude, all four models correctly prodicted more than 80% of heart disease status. As we compare the accuracy scores and confusion matrices, the K nearnest neighbor model has the best performance. For future steps, I am very interested in fine tuning each machine learning model to achieve better performances. The accuracy of the KNN model is 90%, which can potentially be improved. We should always aim for perfection for machine learning in the healthcare field because the prediction could potentially save lifes.

Further, I also hope to read more articles on model selection and comparison. It would be save a lot of time and resources if I was able to select the best performing model from the very beginning. I plan to get more educated on the ideal context to use different machine learning models.
